<span class=dateline>August    27, 2003</span> - Craig 'Silirrion' Morrison was lucky enough to be in London for the ECTS gaming show! There he sat down with Bill Trost and got an extensive look at EverQuest II! <BR>
<BR>
The screenshots were a general release and appear all around the net, while Craig himself took the four exclusive photographs!<BR>
<BR>
You may <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/message.asp?topic=55504361&replies=0">comment on this</A> over on our <A HREF="http://vnboards.ign.com/board.asp?brd=22210">EverQuest II Board!</A><BR>
<BR>
<HR><BR>
<CENTER><B>EverQuest II at ECTS</B><BR>
by Craig 'Silirrion' Morrison</CENTER><BR>
<BR>
<B>Norrath Reborn</B><BR>
<BR>
Firstly before I start I need to say that when it comes to all things Everquest I am a cynic, not your normal, never played before sceptic, but your hard-boiled, played to level sixty (didn't have all these fancy extra levels in my day) and got very bored type of cynic. I played other games and came to wonder if all that downtime in Everquest was worth the effort.<BR>
<BR>
So was I the best person to corner EQ2 lead designer Bill Trost and SOE PR Director Chris Kramer, at the ECTS games conference in London this week? Possibly not, but over the course of an hour or so, as we spoke at length about the sequel and all things Everquest something in me began to melt away, a reformed cynic in the making? Read on and discover what exactly started to get me thinking.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Hey Good looking...</B><BR>
<BR>
The first thing that strikes you about Everquest 2, even in the alpha build that I was being walked through is the sheer quality of the visuals, the graphics are certainly very impressive, but how would your average home machine cope? Chris though quickly put my mind at rest explaining the all the settings in Everquest 2 will be completely scalable and given that the game is shooting for a 2004 release, they are confident that even an average platform will be able to run the game smoothly.<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="http://mediaviewer.ign.com/ignMediaPage.jsp?media_id=1797508&article_id=435630&channel_id=253&page_title=EverQuest+II+at+ECTS%21&adString=network%3Dign%26site%3Deqvault%26pagetype%3Dmediaimgfat&return_url=http%3A%2F%2Feqvault.ign.com%2Farticles%2F435%2F435630p1.html"><IMG SRC="http://eqvaultmedia.ign.com/eqvault/image/t_eq2_ects_1.jpg" BORDER="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="http://mediaviewer.ign.com/ignMediaPage.jsp?media_id=1797509&article_id=435630&channel_id=253&page_title=EverQuest+II+at+ECTS%21&adString=network%3Dign%26site%3Deqvault%26pagetype%3Dmediaimgfat&return_url=http%3A%2F%2Feqvault.ign.com%2Farticles%2F435%2F435630p1.html"><IMG SRC="http://eqvaultmedia.ign.com/eqvault/image/t_eq2_ects_2.jpg" BORDER="0"></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><BR>
<BR>
Bill launched the game and showed me the new character creation screens, complete with a new playable race, a rat like evil breed adept as scouts and mages, bringing the total to sixteen. If you thought Star Wars Galaxies had a diverse character creation interface you haven't seen anything yet! Each race has literally thousands upon thousands of possible permutations.<BR>
<BR>
From earrings and studs, to tattoos, skin colour and hairstyle, there is every possibility that each and every player would be able to carve themselves a unique look. Hitting the random generation button for a few minutes was enough to demonstrate that finding your own look will not be hard at all.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Familiar but not...</B><BR>
<BR>
The world itself  (at least the parts of it we could see in this build) looked very nice, and the city of Freeport in particular had a very good feel and design to it. Whilst many of the original locations will be present in the sequel, they have changed drastically in the five hundred years since the time period the original game is set in.<BR>
<BR>
<CENTER><TABLE><TR><TD><A HREF="http://mediaviewer.ign.com/ignMediaPage.jsp?media_id=1797512&article_id=435630&channel_id=253&page_title=EverQuest+II+at+ECTS%21&adString=network%3Dign%26site%3Deqvault%26pagetype%3Dmediaimgfat&return_url=http%3A%2F%2Feqvault.ign.com%2Farticles%2F435%2F435630p1.html"><IMG SRC="http://eqvaultmedia.ign.com/eqvault/image/t_eq2_ects_freeport.jpg" BORDER="0"></A></TD><TD><A HREF="http://mediaviewer.ign.com/ignMediaPage.jsp?media_id=1797510&article_id=435630&channel_id=253&page_title=EverQuest+II+at+ECTS%21&adString=network%3Dign%26site%3Deqvault%26pagetype%3Dmediaimgfat&return_url=http%3A%2F%2Feqvault.ign.com%2Farticles%2F435%2F435630p1.html"><IMG SRC="http://eqvaultmedia.ign.com/eqvault/image/t_eq2_ects_3.jpg" BORDER="0"></A></TD></TR></TABLE></CENTER><BR>
<BR>
So veterans will immediately identify with certain areas and even certain factions that have maintained a presence, but will also have the wonder of discovery again. As Bill took me on a tour of the new style Freeport the first thing that struck me was the scale, gone is the almost 'building block' style of the old engine and in its place is a sweeping cityscape with spires, towers and paths winding their way between them.<BR>
<BR>
The architecture is very impressive and dwarfs anything seen in the original, as we moved into a new section of the city Bill pointed out several larger buildings, explaining that they were guild halls that the players could earn and own. (More about that later!), scattered between these great guildhalls were smaller individual dwellings that are to be player housing.<BR>

